00:12:49.089 --> 00:12:52.399
There are a variety of potential ingredients
that can cause a difference here.

00:12:52.399 --> 00:12:57.060
For instance, with many diet sodas that contain
aspartame, they end up producing more foam

00:12:57.060 --> 00:13:01.601
because aspartame lowers the surface tension
of the liquid much more than sugar or corn

00:13:01.601 --> 00:13:02.601
syrup will.

00:13:02.601 --> 00:13:06.899
It's possible Coca-Cola simply contains more
surfactants than Dr. Pepper.

00:13:06.899 --> 00:13:11.410
Or it's possible Dr. Pepper just contains
much less carbon dioxide than Coca-Cola; given

00:13:11.410 --> 00:13:15.449
the amount of carbon dioxide dissolved in
the beverage greatly influences the taste

00:13:15.449 --> 00:13:19.949
and mouth feel, we're presuming there is a
reasonable variance from flavor to flavor.

00:13:19.949 --> 00:13:24.540
And, anecdotally, it does always seem like
Dr. Pepper goes flat much faster than a lot

00:13:24.540 --> 00:13:26.160
of soft drinks....

00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:27.720
But that's an experiment for another day.

00:13:27.720 --> 00:13:31.060
For now, whatever is the underlying cause,
we thought it was interesting to note how

00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:35.939
much less foam an equally shaken can of Dr.
Pepper produces compared to a can of Coke.

